@NODE "REQ" "Do you Know ?"
@NEXT "MAIN"
@PREV "COPYRIG"
@TOC "MAIN"
@Font Helvetica.font 13
@{jcenter}


Lately I have come to recognize that the effectiveness of the
byterun1 compression mode PPaint and DPaint are using is highly
linked with the position of the used colors of your palette.
It seems that the compression works best with the first colors
and loses a lot of effectiveness towards the last ones, which
can lead to size differences of up to 200KB with large files
simply because of a different arranged palette (just try a
16 color Picture, paint a big filled circle in the last palette
color, save it, swap the first and the last color in your palette,
use the remap function and save again under a different name.
Although the pictures are absolutely identical except for the
palette arrangement, the filesizes differ about over 40% !!).
Because this can lead to a big waste of bandwidth in the net,
I was searching for a tool that can determin the frequency of
the palette colors, rearrange the palette according to this and
finaly remap the picture to the new palette. Because I was unable
to find such a tool, a little help from you would be most apreciated.
If you know about some Program which could do this job even with
big pictures, please write me so I can reduce my files sice, the
net can save bandwidth, and the world can be a happier place.
Thank´s for your efforts.

@ENDNODE

